Intro

The software package exDE (\(\hookrightarrow \boxdot\)) was designed to help people build, solve, and analyze systems of differential equations describing malaria and other mosquito-transmitted pathogens. The underlying mathematical framework supports nimble model building: models for malaria transmission dynamics and control – potentially including well-developed models for mosquito ecology – are modular, flexible, and extensible. Using this framework and the supporting software, it is easy to build malaria models that are realistic enough to serve the needs of malaria programs [1]. Very complex models can be developed by passing simple scripts or instructions to exDE::xde_setup(), and new models can be developed by modifying existing models. A rigid mathematical framework constrains the computational interface for interactions among the major dynamical components of a model, so the end user can build or modify models with some guarantees of mathematical consistency. The end user can imagine a model that would serve some needs in analysis to support malaria policy, and then call on code that has already been developed to build it without having to learn all of the numerical recipes and coding that are required. The software dramatically lowers the costs of doing simulation-based analytics that are easily replicated, and to do it with code that has been tested and verified so that the computation is done with a high degree of competence.

The role of exDE is similar to the role of a high-end scientific calculator. Solving or analyzing a malaria model in exDE is like computing \(\sqrt{2}\). At one point, you might have learned a simple algorithm to compute it (e.g. a bisection algorithm), but it’s also possible to push a button on your calcluator, if it’s the fancy kind. Since we’re working in R, which has all that same functionality, we can simply compute it:

sqrt(2)
## [1] 1.414214

It’s instructive, perhaps even fun, to learn something like the algorithm for computing \(\sqrt{2}\), but you can just run a command or push the button.

The buttons on a calculator define its capabilities. A calculator can’t do your thinking for you, and most of the buttons aren’t useful until you understand the underlying mathematics. On the other hand, once you know what you want to do, you can usually get the calculator to compute it.

Like a calculator, exDE has built-in models and functionality that define its functional capabilities. Some of the models are there to teach people about malaria, but they lack the skill-set (\(\hookrightarrow \boxdot\)) required to address some critical questions. Other models are there to statisfy the goal of doing analytics robustly (\(\hookrightarrow \boxdot\)). The most important thing is to understand malaria well enough to ask the right questions. The software makes it easy to use models to answer those questions.

It’s often useful if someone understands the underlying mathematics and knows how the software works. Someone should understand how a calculator works. Malaria policy teams should employ or consult with a few numerically competent people who know what’s going on under the hood of exDE – perhaps to flag issues that might get missed otherwise – but it’s awfully useful to have software that is up to tasks.

Using exDE, it’s very easy to set up and solve models. To illustrate, the following sets up and solves one version of the Ross-Macdonald model, based on a paper by Aron & May [2]. It’s default setting for xde_setup() so it would only take a line. We want to modify it a bit to show off.

First, we set up some options so that forced emergence has a sinusoidal seasonal pattern:

Lo = list(Lt = function(t, pars){(1.01+sin(2*pi*t/365))^2})

Now we set up the model:

xde_setup("ross_macdonald", Lopts = Lo) -> ross_macdonald

It takes one more line to solve it, which we attach to the model object:

ross_macdonald <- xde_solve(ross_macdonald, Tmax=2000)

A function returns the variables by name, so we can plot the quantities with ease:

par(mfrow = c(2,1), mar = c(5,4,1,3))
plot_PR(ross_macdonald, nix=1:5) 
xde_plot_eir(ross_macdonald)

It’s not quite as easy as computing \(\sqrt{2}\), but it’s a lot easier than writing the code from scratch. Perhaps more importantly, the code is designed to be easy to read and understand, and there are built-in utilities to build and solve models that can be highly realistic.

The xde_setup() function from exDE is an easy way of building very complex models. (We discuss the topic in the setup tab that follows, but we introduced modular notation already. You can read about it as html) and as a pdf supplement to Spatial Dynamics of Malaria Transmission [1].

The software we wrote was designed to support nimble model building. We wanted to make it easy to deal with a very large set of mathematical issues – mainly numerical and computational – using the mathematics, while drawing as little attention to the math as possible. With this tool in hand, we hope to make it easier to use models in policy discussions that focus on the data, concepts, and decisions.

We don’t want to give a wrong impression: we recognize that malaria is complex, so addressing policy issues with a high degree of competence requires careful thought that is based on a thorough understanding of malaria programs, malaria epidemiology, mosquito ecology, transmission, and the models. Even with knowledge and intuition, walking through the steps required to do an analysis requires hard work and effort to construct a well-designed, creative and critical analysis. The software can help, but someone will have to get their hands dirty. Once it has been developed, it can be easily replicated. The point of this software is to reduce the costs of doing all the things required to do it well.

What are the problems we trying to solve? The big picture here is to eliminate malaria, and meanwhile to save as many lives as possible. These activities required to achieve these goals are ultimately managed by national malaria programs. Some part of the challenges facing malaria programs involve managing the human element and logistics. The decisions and policies are usually based on data collected through routine surveillance collected through health management information systems (HMIS).

Turning data into information, and then turning information into policy advice goes well beyond doing a cursory examination of the routine surveillance data. The challenges facing malaria programs are how to use their HMIS data to understand what is happening in their communities, including evaluation of ongoing malaria control efforts. This involves some kind of synthesis. National malaria programs should be actively working to identify and gather data they need to make good policy decisions. All this requires a linked set of activities to try and understand how malaria in communities. HMIS data must be aligned with research data to try and understand the causes of the biases in the data and the processes – mosquito ecology and transmission, care seeking and treatment, and vector control – that make up the dynamics and control of malaria.

The software was designed to fill a specific role within a broader ecosystem of software and analysis. We expect that the analysis will be done by a team and that some members of the team will have the required expertise, when it is needed. We also expect the discussions to be focused on the core challenges, and not on the technical details required for implementation.

That being said, there’s a lot to learn, because the software covers a lot of topics (see the Figure, below)

xde_setup

\(\oplus\)

Most people are introduced to malaria transmission through the Ross-Macdonald model (reviewed at PLoS Pathogens) [3], usually in a college course, but after that course, there’s still a lot to learn.

exDE has a modular design and built-in features to handle most aspects of mosquito ecology or malaria transmission dynamics and control. Model building involves making a set of choices about the core dynamics, the structural elements, and a set of options that can add realism to the models. The set of choices can be overwhelming, so we start with simple models and build in complexity one piece at a time. We gave the name “scalable complexity” to the design principle that guided development of exDE that makes all this possible.

We put a lot of time into the design of exDE to implement the plug-and-play design. In the design phase, we made a lot of mistakes – decisions that made it difficult to combine or extend the model in other ways. In designing the computational interface, we had to think carefully about each feature and decide how it would have to interact with other model features. If you use the tools that come with exDE – including mob_setup and mob_work – a lot of this is invisible to the end user. If you decide to build models by hand, you might find your work more difficult.

  • Dynamics – the dynamical systems describing mosquito ecology and infection dynamics, and the dynamics of parasite infections in humans.

  • Structure – the configuration of aquatic habitats; patch dynamics; and human population strata to deal with heterogeneity

Model Configuration Options

Pipeline

Scaling

-

Before we apply the framework, it’s worth learning a bit about the built-in functionality and capabilities. In malaria, we measure exposure to malaria entomologically using a metric called the entomological inoculation rate (EIR), and we measure infection using a metric called the parasite rate (PR). The PR is frequently measured, but the EIR is not, so we want to establish a basis for estimating the EIR from the PR, even though the causal relationship goes in the other direction. An important factor is that the PR tends to vary by age.

Studies have identified several factors that affect this relationship (See Figure 1):

  • Every model proposes a slightly different baseline relationship between the EIR and the PR.

  • The PR is affected by taking drugs that cure infections and provide a few weeks of chemoprotection.

  • Exposure to malaria is heterogeneous:

    • In most places, exposure to malaria is seasonal.

    • Heterogeneous biting is a kind of frailty – different strata can have different exposure rates for many reasons. The model handles this kind of heterogeneity through search weights, which are integrated into simulations through the algorithms that compute blood feeding and transmission. An important factor here is age.

    • Environmental heterogeneity describes the distribution of the mean rate of exposure in a population: we formulate a hazard rate that is consistent with the observation that the number of infectious bites, per person, will tend to follow a negative binomial distribution. This affects the functional relationship between the EIR and the FoI.

  • An important part of exposure includes travel and exposure to malaria away from home.

  • When we predict the PR, we want to be aware of context and methods, so we consider the observational process. What methods were used to catch mosquitoes? What was the study design, and how well could the methods detect infection?

These factors are summarized in Figure 1.

Figure 1

We start with the problem of understanding the relationship between the EIR and thidentifying models that we can trust.

eir2pr

In mob_work, we developed the eir2pr family of functions. Each model implies a scaling relationship between the EIR and the PR. It’s too hard to deal with everything all at once, but we can add complexity one step at a time.

plot_eirpr = function(eirpr){
  plot(eirpr, xaxt = "n", log = "x", xlab = "aEIR", ylab = "PR", type = "l")
  axis(1, 10^c(-1:3), c(".1", "1", "10", "100","1000")) 
}

This is the simple SIS model with two different values for the rate of clearance:

xde_setup ("mod0", MYZname= "Ztrace", Xname = "SIS", Lname ="trace")
mod0$Xpar$r = 1/200
plot_eirpr(eir2pr_steady(mod0))
mod1=mod0
mod1$Xpar$r = 1/100
lines(eir2pr_steady(mod1), col = "darkred")
xde_setup ("mod2", MYZname= "Ztrace", Xname = "SIP", Lname ="trace")
mod2$Xpar$r = 1/200
mod2$Xpar$xi = 1/365
plot_eirpr(eir2pr_steady(mod0))
mod2$Xpar$r = 1/100
lines(eir2pr_steady(mod1), col = "darkred")
lines(eir2pr_steady(mod2), col = "purple")

Dynamics

The algorithms at the core of these models are differential equations describing a system with three components. Each component is defined by a state space and a function that describes changes to the state variables – the derivatives with respect to time.

  • We define a state space describing a human population (\(\cal H\)) and the dynamics of infection and immunity (\(\cal X\)). The model library includes many well-defined models published by others, and some of our own.

  • We define a state space describing an adult mosquito population (\(\cal M\)) and the dynamics of infection and infectiousness (\(\cal YZ\)). The model library includes many standard formulations of adult mosquito dynamics and behavior, including utilities for dealing with mosquito movement and behavioral state models.

  • We define a state space describing an aquatic mosquito population (\(\cal L\)) and the dynamics of eggs hatching, and immature mosquito survival, maturation, pupation, and emergence. The model library includes several dynamical formulations.

Since the point of exDE is to reduce the costs of building models, so we will be working to expand the set of model families that fill these roles. We hope people will ask if the model they need has already been developed, and if so, has it already been added to the library.

An important feature of this framework is that we have developed modules so that each one of these components can be reduced to a trace function.. This is the trivial dynamical model, with null dynamics, but a configurable function that can pass its outputs to other modules.

Structure

\(\oplus\)

We must determine how to stratify the population we’re interested in studying – this is what we mean by structure.

  • \(p\) or nPatches is a critical structural element. If nPatches > 1 then we have a spatial model

  • \(n\) or nStrata is a structural element describing the number of humans in a population made up of strata strata. To set up a model, we do this by passing a vector HPop describing the number of people in each stratum (\(H\)), and nStrata <- length(HPop).

  • \(l\) or nHabitats is a structural element describing the number of aquatic habitats. To set up a model, we pass a vector that has the index of the patch where each habitat can be found, called the membership vector, and nHabitats <- length(membership).

  • \(s\) or nSpecies describes the number of mosquito species (or types) in a model. (NOTE: This hasn’t been implemented yet.)

Configuration

Depending on which model family we chose for each component, we will need to set the values of the parameters and initial conditions.

  • For the state model describing human infections, \(\cal X\), there are a set of parameters that must be set describing infection, immunity, disease, infectiousness, and detection:

    • If nPatches>1 then it is necessary to configure a matrix, called the Time Spent matrix (\(\Theta\)), describing how humans spend their time. compute the Time at Risk matrix;

    • If nStrata>1 then it is necessary to assign Search Weights to each stratum for the blood feeding algorithm.

  • For the state model describing adult mosquitoes, \(\cal MYZ\), there are a set of parameters that must be set describing survival, blood feeding, and infection:

    • To simulate adult mosquito population ecology and parasite infection dynamics in mosquitoes, we adopt a published dynamical model of malaria.

    • For the adult mosquito populations, it is necessary to configure a mosquito demographic matrix \(\Omega\), including mosquito movement;

    • the residence vector identifies the location of home for each human population stratum

    • heterogeneous biting is modeled through a frailty term – each stratum is assigned a search weights that affect mosquito blood feeding behavior

  • A built-in model of blood feeding can be used to compute blood feeding rates (\(f\)) and the human blood fraction (\(q\)), and transmission terms are computed through a structured interface that computes a mixing matrix, \(\beta\);

  • \(l\) or nHabitats is a structural element

    • each habitat has a location in a patch;

    • the membership vector is the index of the patch where each habitat is found;

    • egg laying is determined by location and a set of habitat search weights

Options

Some important options for humans are:

  • Human demography is computed as part of \(\cal X\), but it is a set of options \(\cal H\) that can be configured to handle:

    • Cohort dynamics and aging;

    • Births and deaths

  • Malaria Importation can be configured with importation through travel malaria (\(\delta\)) or visitors

  • Exposure models convert the local EIR into the FoI:

    • \(F_h\) is a model for environmental heterogeneity in local exposure

    • pre-erythrocytic immunity, \(F_b\), can be configured

    • the travel FoI is to the local FoI.

  • Mass Medical Interventions can be added to any model, including MDA.

  • Vector Control can be added to any model

  • Exogenous Forcing by weather and a range of other can be configured. The exogenous variables are computed separately:

    • There is a built-in function to compute the time-varying EIP, and the software was designed to compute survival and dispersal in delay differential equations with time-varying EIPs.

    • Models for mosquito ecology and behaviors can be modified by temperature, rainfall, and relative humidity.

  • Health System

xde_setup

xde_setup is an easy way to build a prototype. It is now defined in exDE

To set up a model, the following arguments are passed to xde_setup. All of these arguments are assigned default values that can be overwritten by passing a different value (e.g. MYZname = "GeRM"):

  • modelName - assign a name to the model

  • Dynamical Components

    • MYZname [character] - the name (in quotes) of a \(\cal MYZ\) model (default = “RM”)

    • Xname [character] - the name (in quotes) of a \(\cal X\) model (default = “SIS”)

    • Lname [character] - the name (in quotes) of a \(\cal L\) model (default = “trace”)

  • Model Structure

    • nPatches [numeric] (integer) - the number of patches

    • HPop [vector] (integer) :: \(\rightarrow\) nStrata = length(HPop) - the number of humans in each stratum

    • membership [vector] (integer) ::\(\rightarrow\) nHabitats = length(membership) the \(i^{th}\) element of membership is the index of the patch where the \(i^{th}\) habitat is found

  • Adult Mosquito Options

    • MYZopts [list] :: a list of arguments to set options in either MYZpar or MYZinits

    • calK [matrix] or [character] :: if calK is a matrix, then it becomes MYZpar$calK. If calK is a name, then it dispatches another instance of make_calK (see setup_calK)

    • calKopts [list] :: a set of configuration options for make_calK

  • Human Options

    • Xopts [list] :: a set of configuration options for Xpar or Xinits

    • Hopts [list] :: a set of configuration options for Hpar

    • residence [vector] (integer) & length(residence) == nPatches :: the \(i^{th}\) element of residence is the index of the patch where the \(i^{th}\) stratum resides.

    • searchB [vector] (numeric) & length(searchB) == nStrata :: the blood feeding search weight for each stratum.

    • TaR [matrix] or [character] :: if TaR is a matrix, then it becomes Hpar$TaR. If TaR is a name, then it dispatches another instance of make_TaR (see setup_TaR)

    • TaRopts [list] :: a set of configuration options for make_TaR

  • Aquatic Mosquito Options

    • Lopts [list] :: a set of configuration options for Lpar or Linits

    • searchQ [vector] (numeric) & length(searchQ) == nHabitats :: the egg laying search weight for each aquatic habitat

BIMEP

-

We will demonstrate the capabilities of the software using the example of malaria on Bioko Island, Equatorial Guinea. Intensive malaria control was implemented on Bioko Island starting in 2004. The data we use come from the Bioko Island Malaria Elimination Program (BIMEP). The goal of these simulation-based analytics are to support analysis of ongoing vector control, which includes:

  • distribution of long-lasting, insecticide treated bed nets (LLINs)

  • indoor residual spraying (IRS)

  • starting this year, larval source management (LSM)

We would like to understand malaria transmission now as a changing baseline that has been modified by vector control. Our analysis will start simple and add realism one step at a time. This demonstrates the capabilities of exDE and it also establishes a simple method for replicating this sort of analysis for other systems. Among the problems we would like to address:

  • Malaria Importation: Several papers have described the problem of malaria importation [4]…

  • Age

A core challenge is that we would like to develop a quantitative understanding of malaria using the data we have.
